SCUDO: Signature-based Clustering for Diagnostic Purposes

Matteo Ciciani1, Thomas Cantore1 and Enrica Colasurdo1

1CIBIO, Univ. of Trento, Trento, Italy

2018-06-10

Abstract

This package implements in R the SCUDO pipeline proposed in Lauria (2013) and Lauria, Moyseos, Priami (2015).

1 An introduction about the method

The aim of SCUDO is to work as a classifier for microarray-based phenotype prediction. The method is based on the idea of a sample-specific signature. The expected result is the emergence of a partitioning of the set of samples in separate groups on the basis of signature similarity.
A first normalization step and feature selection are optionally performed. Feature selection is obtained through a Wilcoxon Rank Sum Statistics or Kruskal-Wallis Rank Sum Test depending on number of sample groups considered.
The subsequent operations include single sample gene ranking and signature extraction (based on UpSignatures, DownSignatures values). An all-to-all distance matrix is then computed using a metric similar to the Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA): the distance is calculated finding an enrichment score (ES) of the signature of one sample against the whole list of sorted IDs.
Consensus signtures, both for up- and down-signatures are then computed, in order to extract the overall most relevant signatures, for each of the considered groups. 
Finally, a threshold as the Nth lowest percentile of distances is used in order to produce a map as a graph, where each node represents signatures and each node is connected by an edge corresponding to their respective distance. The map can be displayed through the use of Cytoscape.

2 Example

Example using the ALL package, containing data of T- and B-cell Acute Lymphocytic Leukemia.

2.1 Load required packages and explore data

library(scudo)
library(ALL)
data(ALL)

We can extract the expression data and the samples annotation.

expData <- exprs(ALL)
dim(expData)
#> [1] 12625   128
phenoData <- pData(ALL)

expData contains mRNA expression measurements for 128 samples and 12625 features. The factor phenoData$BT classifies the samples as B- or T-cell lymphocytic leukemia:

summary(phenoData$BT)
#>  B B1 B2 B3 B4  T T1 T2 T3 T4 
#>  5 19 36 23 12  5  1 15 10  2

We can see that there are different classes of B- and T-cell leukemia. For now we can simplify this, keeping only the distinction between B- and T-cells.

bt <- as.factor(stringr::str_extract(phenoData$BT, "^."))
summary(bt)
#>  B  T 
#> 95 33

2.2 Perform analysis

Rigth now the input has to be a data.frame, soon we will add matrices and ExpressionSets.

expData <- as.data.frame(expData)
ScudoRes <- scudo(expData, groups = bt, nTop = 100, nBottom = 100, pValue = 0.1)
ScudoRes
#> Scudo Results Object 
#> 
#> Class                  :  ScudoResults 
#> Number of samples      :  128 
#> UpSignatures           :  100 
#> DownSignatures         :  100 
#> Number of groups       :  2 
#> Normalization          :  TRUE 
#> Feature selection         
#>   Performed            :  TRUE 
#>   Test                 :  Wilcoxon Rank Sum statistic 
#>   pValue               :  0.1 
#>   p.adj method         :  none 
#>   selected features    :  5468

From this object we can extract the signatures for each sample and the consensus signatures for each group.

UpSig <- UpSignatures(ScudoRes)
UpSig[1:5,1:5]
#>      01005      01010    03002      04006    04007
#> 1 36543_at    1183_at 36543_at   36638_at 40367_at
#> 2 35362_at   37006_at 33462_at   34721_at 36638_at
#> 3 40953_at   32523_at 33910_at 37251_s_at  1113_at
#> 4 36275_at   40749_at 36275_at   40763_at 35352_at
#> 5 39389_at 38522_s_at 38510_at   34106_at 36908_at
ConsUpSig <- ConsensusUpSignatures(ScudoRes)
ConsUpSig[1:5, ]
#>            B         T
#> 1 38096_f_at  38319_at
#> 2 38095_i_at  38147_at
#> 3   35016_at  33238_at
#> 4   37039_at  37078_at
#> 5   39839_at 2059_s_at

The object ScudoRes can be used to generate a network of samples, as an igraphobject, using the function ScudoNetwork.

net <- ScudoNetwork(ScudoRes, N = 0.2)

The parameter N controls the percentage of edges to keep in the network. We can plot this network using the usual plot function.

plot(net)

This plot is useful to have a quick look at the network, but is rather ugly. We can render the network in Cytoscape, using the function ScudoCytoscape. Note that Cytoscape has to be open when running the function.

ScudoCytoscape(net)
